{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"680ca087-d77c-40e1-b5f8-3018136dd29d","content":"No repo-specific docs on this topic, so here's the general guidance:\n\nOn macOS, NativeAOT apps don't bundle `createdump`. To get a crash dump:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app.\n\n2. **Check macOS crash reports** — macOS automatically writes `.ips` / `.crash` files to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n3. **Use `lldb`** — attach to or post-mortem debug:\n   ```\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n   Core files land in `/cores/` (requires SIP adjustments on modern macOS).\n\n4. **Ensure `/cores/` is writable** and that System Integrity Protection (SIP) isn't blocking core file creation. You may need to:\n   ```\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n5. **For .NET-specific managed state**, you can load the SOS debugging extension in `lldb` (if the DAC is available for your runtime) to inspect managed objects in the core file.\n\n**Key caveat:** On Apple Silicon, core dump generation may require disabling `kern.coredump` restrictions via `sysctl`:\n```\nsudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ed6ebcdf-b39c-4a62-89b2-6fcee392a01e","outputTokens":339},"id":"2a0abfda-ff1c-485c-a658-5e6bb29f71f0","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:01:15.335Z","parentId":"a4632309-1e1a-4b7d-b91e-6b3b458071e4"}
